STA108 Project - A Case Study of the Effect of Pollution on Mortality

Chris Cheng, Richard Takiar, Truc Le

8/1/2019

Our data observe how the rate of mortality in a city responds to the variables such as annual precipitation, education level, percentage of nonwhite individuals, percentage of poor people, pollution of nitrogen oxides, and sulphur dioxide. Our goal of the analysis is to fit a regression model that best represents the trends of the data.

# transform the X variables NOx and SO2 with natural log
# transform the X variables NONWHITE and POOR with cube root
Mortality.trans <- mutate(Mortality, NOX = log(NOX), SO2 = log(SO2),
                         NONWHITE = NONWHITE^(1/3), POOR = POOR^(1/3))

# re-plot the matrix plot of the transformed dataset
#pdf(file="Rplot_trans.pdf", paper = "a4r", width = 40)
plot(Mortality.trans, lower.panel=NULL)

#dev.off()

Mortality.corr <- Mortality.trans[,-8]
M <- cor(Mortality.corr)
corrplot(M, method="number", type="upper")

full.model <- lm(MORTALITY~., data=Mortality.corr); full.model

Full Regression Model Estimated Beta Coefficients (Rounded to 4 decimal points)

The regression model fit here is as follows: \[\LARGE Y_i=\beta_0+\beta_1X_1+\beta_2X_2+\beta_3X_3+\beta_4X_4+\beta_5X_5+\beta_6X_6+\varepsilon\]

Intercept PRECIP EDUC NONWHITE POOR NOX SO2
980.475 2.375 -19.100 49.905 -31.098 10.104 8.031

The estimated regression formation equation is therefore as follows: \[\large \hat{Y} = 980.475+2.375X_1-19.100X_2+49.905X_3-31.098X_4+10.104X_5+8.031X_6\]

NONWHITE Data Non-linear Transformation

We believe that the matrix plot of Mortality (Y) vs. NONWHITE (X) appears to look nonlinear and may be better fitted with a polynomial regression model.

y <- Mortality.corr$MORTALITY
X <- Mortality.corr$NONWHITE
x <- X - mean(X)
x2 <- x^2

fit.nonw <- lm(MORTALITY~Mortality.corr$NONWHITE, data=Mortality.corr) 
fit.nonw.poly <- lm(y~x+x2)

plot(Mortality.corr$NONWHITE, Mortality.corr$MORTALITY, 
     ylab='Mortality (deaths per 100,000)', 
     xlab='Nonwhite Population Percentage', main='')
points(X, fit.nonw$fitted.values, type='l', col='blue')
points(X[order(x)], fit.nonw.poly$fitted.values[order(x)], type='l', col='red')

SO2 Data Non-Linear Transformation

We believe that the matrix plot of Mortality (Y) vs. NONWHITE (X) appears to look nonlinear and may be better fitted with a polynomial regression model.

y <- Mortality.corr$MORTALITY
X1 <- Mortality.corr$SO2
x1 <- X1 - mean(X1)
x2.1 <- (x1)^2

fit.SO2 <- lm(MORTALITY~Mortality.corr$SO2, data=Mortality.corr) 
fit.SO2.poly <- lm(y~x1+x2.1)

plot(Mortality.corr$SO2, Mortality.corr$MORTALITY, 
     ylab='Mortality (deaths per 100,000)', xlab='Relative Pollution 
     Potential of sulphur dioxide', main='')
points(X1, fit.SO2$fitted.values, type='l', col='blue')
points(X1[order(x1)], fit.SO2.poly$fitted.values[order(x1)], type='l', col='red')

Fit New Model with Nonlinear Terms

\(\ Y = 1156.7132 \ + 2.1021X_1 \ -19.2041X_2 \ + 53.9390X_3 \ + 15.4809X_3^2 \ -44.7977X_4 \ + 7.7489X_5 \ + 9.0978X_6 \ + 0.3558X_6^2 \ + \epsilon\)

Model Selection Procedure

As a result of selecting the most appropriate model for our transformed data, we ran the default forward selection and backward elimination as well as the stepwise versions and all subsets regression. From these procedures we found that nonlinear predictors, SO2 and NONWHITE were not significant in predicting mortality.

# Conduct all subsets regression on non-linearity term full model
Mortality.corr <- mutate(Mortality.corr, x_nonw=x, 
                         x2_nonw=x2, x_so2=x1, x2_so2x=x2.1)
Mortality.corr.new <- Mortality.corr[,-c(4,7)]

selection <- leaps(x=Mortality.corr.new[,-1],
                   y=Mortality.corr.new[,1], method = 'Cp')
index <- order(selection$Cp, decreasing = FALSE)
index.values <- sort(selection$Cp, decreasing = FALSE)
best.models <- selection$which[index, ]

Best model has Predictors 1, 2, 5, 7 which is PRECIP, EDUC, x_nonw, x_so2 with Mallow’s \(C_p\) of \(4.3329\).

## - x       1   28331.7 98209 454.03
## 
## Step:  AIC=435.38
## MORTALITY ~ PRECIP + EDUC + x + x1
## 
##          Df Sum of Sq    RSS    AIC
## <none>                 71965 435.38
## - EDUC    1      6397  78361 438.48
## - PRECIP  1     13285  85249 443.54
## - x1      1     24882  96847 451.19
## - x       1     42621 114586 461.28
# partial R^2 calculation from adding NONWHITE quadratic term to "Best" model
best.reduced.NON <- lm(MORTALITY~PRECIP+EDUC+x+x1, data=Mortality.corr)
best.full.NON <- lm(MORTALITY~PRECIP+EDUC+x+x2+x1, data=Mortality.corr)

SSE.red <- ((anova(best.reduced.NON))[5,2])
SSE.full <- ((anova(best.full.NON))[6,2])
partial.R2.NON <- (SSE.red-SSE.full)/SSE.full

There is a \(\Large 1.60\%\) reduction in residual sum of squares when adding a quadratic term for data on the population percentage in 1960 that is nonwhite to a model containing the linear term for data on said population percentage, the linear term for data on SO2 pollution potential, the mean annual precipitation, and the median number of school years completed by persons aged \(25\) or older.

# partial R^2 calculation from adding SO2 quadratic term to the "Best" model
best.reduced.SO2 <- lm(MORTALITY~PRECIP+EDUC+x+x1, data=Mortality.corr)
best.full.SO2 <- lm(MORTALITY~PRECIP+EDUC+x+x2.1+x1, data=Mortality.corr)

SSE.red <- ((anova(best.reduced.SO2))[5,2])
SSE.full <- ((anova(best.full.SO2))[6,2])
partial.R2.SO2 <- (SSE.red-SSE.full)/SSE.full

There is a \(\Large 0.20\%\) reduction in residual sum of squares when adding a quadratic term for data on the relative pollution potential of sulphur dioxide to a model containing the linear term for data on said relative pollution potential, the mean annual precipitation, and the median number of school years completed by persons aged \(25\) or older.

Conclusion

All of the model selection techniques result with the same final model, Y ~ PRECIP + EDUC + x_nonwhite + x_so2. We first had to transform the nitrogen oxide and sulphur dioxide predictors using the natural log function and the nonwhite and poor predictors using the cube root function. We found that the percentage of nonwhite people in the population and pollution of SO_2 predictor variables were quadratic in nature in how they related to mortality by observing the scatter plot matrix and residuals vs predictor plots. We preformed diagnostics on that transformed data and observed that the fitted Y values against the Y values plot is approximately linear which tells us that there is not much error between our observed data and our regression model. In our residual vs fitted Y values plot, histogram of residuals, and QQ plot we observed that our distribution of errors is normal.
